  "format": "Sean and Amanda pitch ten fixes for a pandemic-scrambled 2021 Oscars, then Alex Ross Perry on trying to make movies when the money and the theaters have gone.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Ten Ways to Save the 2021 Oscars",
      "note": "Sean and Amanda pitch reforms",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "No Time to Die",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "The James Bond film's second delay kicks off the discussion, the clearest sign the release calendar is collapsing; the Broccolis move it to 2021 to protect it from a crowded November."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Sean announces its delay mid-recording as breaking news, proof the December slate is emptying out."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wonder Woman 1984",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "One of the last mainstream tentpoles still nominally on the 2020 calendar."
        },
        {
          "title": "Tenet",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "The one Warner Bros. forced into theaters; the studios' test case for pushing through."
        },
        {
          "title": "Minari",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "A24's Steven Yeun drama, the case study for building an Oscar campaign for a small film without theaters or a marketing budget."
        },
        {
          "title": "On the Rocks",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Sofia Coppola's new one, out October 23 on Apple TV+; the show plans to celebrate it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Witches",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Zemeckis's $100M Roald Dahl adaptation dropping straight to HBO Max, cited as early evidence the theatrical window is collapsing."
        },
        {
          "title": "Greenland",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "The Gerard Butler disaster film that skipped theaters for PVOD and then HBO Max."
        },
        {
          "title": "Extraction",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Named as a Best Stunt contender under the proposed new category."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bad Boys for Life",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Also floated as a Best Stunt candidate in a thin year for big action."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Star Is Born",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Sean's rare example of a Best Original Song that actually served the movie, arguing to scrap the category otherwise."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Alex Ross Perry on the Collapse",
      "guest": "Alex Ross Perry on",
      "note": "the writer-director on quarantine, financing, and his horror season",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Her Smell",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Perry's Elizabeth Moss film, his benchmark for the sub-$10M movie he says he couldn't finance now."
        },
        {
          "title": "Listen Up Philip",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "The kind of micro-budget, actor-dependent film he built a career on and now can't cast."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mank",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Perry's shorthand for Netflix's strategy: one prestige Fincher film beats five Devil All the Times."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Devil All the Time",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "The rare risky indie Netflix picked up between shooting and release, an outlier in an otherwise safe slate."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Irishman",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Cited as proof Netflix functions like '90s Touchstone, needing only five aces a year."
        },
        {
          "title": "Manchester by the Sea",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "The Amazon acquisition that worked, picked up finished rather than financed by them."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wonderstruck",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "Todd Haynes's Amazon-era misfire, the kind of auteur bet that burned the studio down."
        },
        {
          "title": "Carol",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "The acclaimed Haynes film that preceded Wonderstruck."
        },
        {
          "title": "Marie Antoinette",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "Sofia Coppola's $40M swing, invoked to marvel that her new film landed with so little heat."
        },
        {
          "title": "Fade to Black",
          "year": 1980,
          "note": "Perry's top horror-season recommendation, on Shudder; a proto-Scream character study he calls an instant four-star movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Gonjiam: Haunted Asylum",
